BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:TU2042192174
DTSTAMP:20260313T210315Z
SUMMARY:Judaism & Environment Class
DESCRIPTION:7:00pm - dinner  \n7:30pm - class starts  \n  \nIn this two-par
 t series\, Rabbinic Intern Jacob Lipkin will explore what Judaism has to s
 ay about our relationship and responsibility for the environment. Particip
 ants may attend one or both sessions.  \n  \nThere will be a light dinner 
 funded by a grant from Shemayim's Synagogue_Vegan_Challenge: https://shama
 yim.us/the-synagogue-vegan-challenge/.   \n  \n**Part 1: Foundations (Janu
 ary 29)**  \nAlready from the very first chapter of the Torah\, Judaism po
 sits an environmental ethic! The Jewish tradition has always been aware th
 at humanity is not alone on this planet\, and that our existence entails a
  profound sense of responsibility. What is the exact nature of that respon
 sibility\, and how has it changed over time? Is it more individual or comm
 unal? We’ll look at the historical development of Jewish environmentalis
 m and consider how plausibly it maps onto contemporary notions of sustaina
 bility.  \n  \n**Part 2: Activism (February 26)**  \nAs long as there have
  been activists\, there have been Jewish activisits\, but for how long hav
 e there been Jewish environmental/climate activists? We’ll survey today
 ’s Jewish institutional climate/sustainability advocacy ecosystem. To wh
 at extent should this sort of work be a communal priority? How can we bala
 nce the vision of leaders and institutions in this regard with a grassroot
 s ethos?   \n  \n**Questions?**  \nContact Jacob Lipkin  \njlipkin@shomrei
 .org\n\n
LOCATION:Social Hall
CATEGORIES:Events
CLASS:PUBLIC
TRANSP:OPAQUE
SEQUENCE:0
